 basilar membrane (BM) of the cochlea has been extensively studied.
 Although numerous models and measurements of the displacement of the BM
 have been reported, there has been little success in the determination
 of its impedance.
 In order to determine the impedance, a known input waveform can induce
 a measured output waveform, allowing for the simple calculation of the
 BM transfer function.
 However, problems arise in the formulation of a protocol for this input
 waveform.
 We now attempt to calculate the feasibility of displacing the BM via bombardmen
t with photons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1871, James Clerk Maxwell proposed the theory that electromagnetic radiation
 can exert a pressure upon any given surface.
 This was later demonstrated by Lebedev in 1901 in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Annalen der Physik.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The conversation of pressures exerted by electromagnetic radiation continued,
 from the Nichols radiometer to the solar sails currently under development
 for space travel.
 The question poised in this protocol is the feasibility of this phenomenon
 to the application of BM displacement.
 
\end_layout

