\begin_layout Section
Basic Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to properly derive the values necessary to determine the forces
 generated by light incident on a particular mirror, the model system must
 first be described.
 Consider the basilar membrane, upon which sits the Organ of Corti (OC).
 When a sound pressure waveform enters the inner ear, the basilar membrane
 is displaced.
 As seen in Figure 1, the location of the peak amplitude of this displacement
 is dependent upon the frequency of input.
 This is known as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

traveling wave
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 hypothesis for the basilar membrane.
 In this particular model, we attempt to displace the basilar membrane directly.
 
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/Josh/Dropbox/Documents/Reference/Photons and Pressure/ch13f5.jpg
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
FIGURE 1.
 Illustration of the human basilar membrane.
 Note that location of the peak amplitude along the length of the BM is
 dependent upon the frequency of input.
 Lower frequencies are situated distal to the stapes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model, a gold plate of minimal thickness and equivalent stiffness
 (dependent upon the location along the BM) is placed on the inferior side
 of the BM, opposite the superior OC.
 This gold plate's shape is assumed to be hexagonal in the following calculation
s, and its weight is assumed to be negligible compared to the BM.
 Its diameter is also assumed to be smaller than the width of the BM for
 a given model organism.
 Calculations below use the gerbil as a model organism, though the equations
 are applicable to all models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon placing the gold plate on the inferior side of the BM, a hole of diameter
 larger than 2t (where t = side length of the hexagonal gold plate) is drilled.
 Through this is passed a laser, assumed in this case to emit ultraviolet
 light.
 The goal is to target the gold plate with this laser, exposing what is
 now a metallic reflector to the momentum of incident photons.
 A question then emerges: Do the incident photons produce enough pressure
 to displace the basilar membrane?
\end_layout

