\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Derivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When considering radiation pressure on a surface, one cannot simply assume
 complete absorption or reflection.
 For a surface with 100% absorption, the equivalent pressure is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{rad}=U/c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and for a surface with 100% reflection, the equivalent pressure is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2) 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{rad}=2\times U/c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where U is the power flux density and c is the speed of light.
 If we assume a linear relationship between these extremes, an equivalent
 relationship can be found:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{rad}=(\eta+1)\times U/c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none
 is the proportion of photons reflected by a given surface, between zero
 and one.
 These equations are derived from a relationship between pressure, force,
 and momentum, as shown below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(4) 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{rad}=F/A=\frac{dp}{dt}/A=U/c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We must now consider the metallic reflector, a gold plate.
 The gold plate's area is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(5) 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{mirror}=\frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}t^{2}=\frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where t is the side length of the hexagonal plate and d is the maximal diameter
 of the hexagon.
 Given this formula, a plate with maximal diameter equal to 100 microns
 would have an area of 6.5E-9 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A larger maximal diameter would grant a greater applied force with a given
 incident radiation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining the above to give a total force applied to the mirror per cycle
 gives the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(6) 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{applied}=\frac{\left(\eta+1\right)\times U}{c}\times\frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An interesting point to note is that the reflectance of a material is dependent
 upon the frequency of the incident light.
 Thus, optimization of the applied force is dependent upon the following
 variables:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Material of the mirror (e.g., gold)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Size of the mirror (e.g., 100 micron diameter)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Laser frequency (e.g., ultraviolet)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Power flux density of the laser
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Input frequency of the sinusoidal waveform (e.g., 3000 Hz)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This information is then only useful if the displacement of the BM can be
 determined.
 If the material is assumed to be linear-elastic, then the displacement
 is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(7) 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=F/k$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where k is the stiffness of the basilar membrane.
\end_layout

