\begin_layout Section
Example Feasibility Calculation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following calculation attempts to use values from the literature using
 the gerbil cochlea as a model.
 Consider an ultraviolet laser with power density flux at either 2.5, 3.33,
 or 4.16 
\begin_inset Formula $J/cm^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We will consider the case with the intermediate value.
 The optical properties of gold predict a reflectance dropping from 99%
 in the visible spectrum to just below 40% in the ultraviolet spectrum.
 The gold mirror will have a side length of 100 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m$
\end_inset

, providing it with a maximal diameter twice that value The gerbil's basilar
 membrane stiffness varies from approximately 9-10 N/m at the cochlear base
 to as low as 0.001 N/m at the uppermost turn.
 The median stiffness of 0.01 N/m will be used, though a higher value may
 be more realistic under experimental conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given these values, the following calculations are performed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F_{applied}=\frac{\left(\eta+1\right)\times U}{c}\times\frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}=\frac{\left(0.40+1\right)\times33300J/m^{2}}{299792458m/s}\times\frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}\left(\frac{0.0002m}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F_{applied}\cong4.04\times10^{-12}\frac{N}{sec}=4.04\frac{pN}{sec}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is this feasible? Let us consider the displacement these incident photons
 would impose:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=F/k=\frac{4.04\times10^{-12}\frac{N}{sec}}{0.01N/m}=4.04\times10^{-10}\frac{m}{sec}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the velocity of the BM upon these incident photons would be on the
 order of 0.404 nm/sec.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discussion and Concerns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above case describes an extreme scenario, with a fairly large gold mirror,
 highly efficient energy transfer, fairly low frequency, and low BM stiffness.
 Given that the velocity of BM displacement is on the lower end of acceptable
 values (those around 1 nm), this causes concern.
 If the experiment were to impose a sinusoidal waveform, this may not be
 enough force to ensure control of the system.
 Thus, the system might be feasible, but the system would require significant
 optimization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One possible solution to this problem is to increase the wavelength of the
 incident laser.
 Note that the reflectance of gold drops to below 40% in the ultraviolet
 spectrum.
 At wavelengths of 700-20000 nm, the reflectance of bare gold is estimated
 to be 99%.
 Light within this range may prove more useful than its ultraviolet counterpart.
 A potential trade-off of such a system, however, could be a drop in the
 power density flux of the laser.
 Considering this is the driving force of the system, optimizing the power
 of the laser may prove more useful.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, no solutions to this problem seem to increase the order of magnitude
 of force generated.
 Thus, minor optimizations could potentially increase velocity of BM displacemen
t by two- or three-fold, but not much further.
 Doing so would allow for 0.4 to 1.0 nm/sec velocities.
 Pulsatile inputs can then formulate the necessary sinusoidal waveform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, the calculations above included numerous assumptions.
 Furthermore, measurement of the displacement was not considered.
 Backscatter could interfere with such measurements.
 Furthermore, the power of the laser was not consider in terms of thermal
 energy produced.
 The goal of such experiments would be to displace the BM without ablating
 it, thus imposing yet another limitation.
 
\end_layout

